The article discusses the implementation of signals intelligence reforms in the United States. In 2014, President Obama directed a series of reforms to ensure that intelligence activities are carried out with appropriate oversight and respect for civil liberties and privacy. The Presidential Policy Directive - 28 (PPD-28) was also signed, which sets limitations on the use of signals intelligence collected in bulk and establishes safeguards for personal information collected through signals intelligence. The Director of National Intelligence is releasing a report highlighting the progress made in implementing these reforms, including reforms regarding the collection of bulk telephony metadata records and intelligence under the Foreign Intelligence Surveillance Act. The Administration has also been implementing recommendations from the President's Review Group on Intelligence and Communications Technologies. The article emphasizes the need to balance national security interests with privacy and civil liberties.